concept_explanation.monotonic:
**Monotonic Stack — maintain sorted order while processing:**

```java
// DECREASING monotonic stack: maintains indices of elements
// in decreasing order of their VALUES
// When we see a value LARGER than stack top:
//   → it's the 'next greater element' for everything it beats
//   → pop and record answers before pushing

int[] nextGreater(int[] nums) {
    int n = nums.length;
    int[] result = new int[n];
    Arrays.fill(result, -1); // default: no greater element
    Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>(); // stores INDICES
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        // While current is greater than stack top's value:
        while (!stack.isEmpty() && nums[i] > nums[stack.peek()]) {
            result[stack.pop()] = nums[i]; // current is next greater
        }
        stack.push(i);
    }
    return result; // elements still in stack have no next greater
}
// Complexity: O(n) — each element pushed/popped at most once
```

worked_example.final_code:
int[] h=new int[]{2,1,5,6,2,3};
Deque<Integer> stack=new ArrayDeque<>();
int maxArea=0;
for(int i=0;i<=h.length;i++){
    int currH=(i==h.length)?0:h[i]; // virtual 0 at end flushes stack
    while(!stack.isEmpty()&&currH<h[stack.peek()]){
        int height=h[stack.pop()];
        int width=stack.isEmpty()?i:i-stack.peek()-1;
        maxArea=Math.max(maxArea,height*width);
    }
    stack.push(i);
}
// returns 10
